markdown <<MARKDOWN
# Where Does AI Fit In?

In this course, AI is a helper, not a replacement for students’ thinking. Students stay in control of the design and coding process, while AI serves as a creative partner that can suggest, outline, or refine ideas.
How Students Use AI
As a brainstorming tool: AI can suggest starting points (like a layout or function idea) that students then adapt and improve.
As a tutor-on-demand: Students can ask AI to explain tricky concepts, find bugs, or show examples—while still doing the reasoning themselves.
As a collaborator in building: AI helps write or refine HTML, CSS, and JavaScript, but students must review, edit, and debug to ensure the code works and matches their vision.
As a critique partner: Students learn to spot bias, errors, or poor design in AI outputs, strengthening their critical evaluation skills.
The Four Creative Modes
The course introduces structured ways to work with AI responsibly:
Suggest → AI offers hints or small code pieces to support student work.
Outline → AI generates a framework with placeholders, and students fill in the logic.
Guide → Students build piece-by-piece, directing AI step by step.
Produce → AI creates a feature from a detailed student plan, which students then refine and evaluate.
Why This Matters
By learning to use AI this way, students practice ethical and intentional coding. They don’t just accept AI’s work blindly—they evaluate it, adapt it, and ensure it aligns with their values, goals, and understanding. This prepares them to work with AI in the real world while keeping ownership of their learning and creations.




#### The Programming with Music Lab curriculum begins with an introductory lesson, <a href="https://studio.code.org/courses/programming-with-music-lab-2025/units/1/lessons/1" target="blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Introduction to Music Lab</a>, which introduces the Problem-Solving Process and primes students to create music.

#### The rest of the curriculum is divided into three chunks, each covering one of the major computer science concepts: **sequencing**, **loops**, and **functions**.

